<subSubSection pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Morphology. D VI + I,12–13; A I,12–13; P 22–23. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[776,946,1081,1107]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Body elongate</emphasis>
, the depth 
<quantity box="[1072,1185,1081,1108]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5367" metricValueMax="1.651" metricValueMin="1.4223999999999999" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="in" value="6.05" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="5.6">5.6–6.5 in</quantity>
standard length. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Eyes protruding, their upper part well above dorsal profile of head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[920,1005,1117,1144]" captionStart="FIGURE 45" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetId="figure-40@39.[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 45. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Oxyurichthys petersii. Photo by J.E. Randall, Port Sudan, Sudan, Red Sea." pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
), each topped by a short fleshy knob. A narrow dermal crest present on nape. Caudal peduncle deep, almost as deep as body. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Spines of first dorsal fin elongate, each ending in a short filament</emphasis>
. Dorsal and anal fins long-based. Pelvic fins united to form a disc. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,403,1225,1251]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Caudal fin lanceolate</emphasis>
, nearly twice as long as head (
<figureCitation box="[741,824,1225,1252]" captionStart="FIGURE 45" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetId="figure-40@39.[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 45. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Oxyurichthys petersii. Photo by J.E. Randall, Port Sudan, Sudan, Red Sea." pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
). Scales on body ctenoid posteriorly, becoming cycloid anteriorly below middle of first dorsal fin, no scales on cheek, opercle, and prepectoral area (
<bibRefCitation author="Pezold, F. L. &amp; Larson, H. K." pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref62939" refString="Pezold, F. L. &amp; Larson, H. K. (2015) A revision of the fish genus Oxyurichthys (Gobioidei: Gobiidae) with descriptions of four new species. Zootaxa, 3988 (1), 1 - 95. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3988.1.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Pezold &amp; Larson 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Scales small, at best visible on body as pattern of pale dots.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Live coloration. Yellowish to greenish gray dorsally, abdomen whitish, 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">with a midlateral row 6 slightly elongate, blackish blotches,</emphasis>
the first blotch on pectoral-fin base, the last on mid caudal peduncle at caudal-fin base (
<figureCitation box="[160,245,1405,1432]" captionStart="FIGURE 45" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetId="figure-40@39.[151,1435,1139,1789]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 45. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Oxyurichthys petersii. Photo by J.E. Randall, Port Sudan, Sudan, Red Sea." pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
), sometimes alternating with 5 smaller dark spots. Head with 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[957,1294,1405,1431]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">a broad dark bar below eye</emphasis>
, indistinctly edged with a pale blue line, followed by a row of dark blotches across operculum. Males with a series of oblique iridescent blue streaks on body, the first below origin of first dorsal fin; membranes of both dorsal fins with yellowish marks, forming longitudinal stripes, separated by short blue stripes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" box="[199,678,1549,1576]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goren &amp; Stern" authorityYear="2021" box="[383,671,1549,1576]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Cryptocentrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="steinhardti">
<emphasis box="[383,671,1549,1576]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Cryptocentrus steinhardti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Habitat. Inhabits silty sand or mud substrata of sheltered bays or estuaries, from the shallows to depths of 
<quantity box="[1372,1432,1585,1612]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" unit="m" value="50.0">50 m</quantity>
; takes refuge in a burrow, but is able to dive quickly into mud if threatened when away from shelter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="70.[151,1437,1045,1828]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Geographic distribution. In the native area restricted to the Red Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Pezold, F. L. &amp; Larson, H. K." box="[956,1212,1657,1684]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref62939" refString="Pezold, F. L. &amp; Larson, H. K. (2015) A revision of the fish genus Oxyurichthys (Gobioidei: Gobiidae) with descriptions of four new species. Zootaxa, 3988 (1), 1 - 95. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3988.1.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Pezold &amp; Larson 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The most common Lessepsian goby migrant in the Mediterranean, where reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[918,997,1693,1719]" name="Greece" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Greece</collectingCountry>
at Kastellorizo Island (
<bibRefCitation author="Apostolopoulos, G. &amp; Karachle, P. K." pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="230 - 252" refId="ref50881" refString="Apostolopoulos, G. &amp; Karachle, P. K. (2016) New records of two fishes in Hellenic Waters (Kastellorizo Island): Scarus ghobban (Forsskal, 1775) and Oxyurichthys petersi (Klunzinger, 1871). In: Karachle, P. K., Angelidis, A., Apostolopoulos, G., Ayas, D., Ballesteros, M., Bonnici, C., Brodersen, M. M., Castriota, L., Chalari, N., Cottalorda, J. M., Crocetta, F., Deidun, A., Dodo, Z., Dogrammatzi, A., Dulcic, J., Fiorentino, F., Gonulal, O., Harmelin, J. G., Insacco, G., Izquierdo-Gomez, D., Izquierdo-Munoz, A., Joksimovic, A., Kavadas, S., Malaquias, M. E., Madrenas, E., Massi, D., Micarelli, P., Minchin, D., Onal, U., Ovalis, P., Poursanidis, D., Siapatis, A., Sperone, E., Spinelli, A., Stamouli, C., Tiralongo, F., Tuncer, S., Yaglioglu, D., Zava, B. &amp; Zenetos, A., New Mediterranean Biodiversity Records (July 2019). Mediterranean Marine Science, 17 (1), pp. 230 - 252. https: // doi. org / 10.12681 / mms. 1684" type="journal article" year="2016">Apostolopoulos &amp; Karachle 2016</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[376,438,1729,1755]" name="Israel" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Israel</collectingCountry>
